(“Fixin’ to” and its AAVE sibling “finna” are interesting because they are basically the same as “going to” or “about to” but “fixin’ to” has the additional connotation that it is something you are currently preparing to do, which “going to” or “about to” do not imply.)

I’ve been saying “fixin’ to” (as in “I’m fixin’ to go to the store) my whole life because it’s a very Southern thing to say but then someone on here pointed out that the phrase may very likely have originated in AAVE (it’s impossible to know for sure) and that’s got me thinking.
